04605nam a22007215i 9780801469060DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014690607 a10.7591/97808014690602doi  a(DE-B1597)515862  a(OCoLC)859229486  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aGN296.5.U33bC73 2013 7aMED0220202bisacsh04a306.4/610967612231 aCrane, Johanna Tayloe, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScrambling for Africa :bAIDS, Expertise, and the Rise of American Global Health Science /cJohanna Tayloe Crane. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b3 halftones, 1 chart, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aExpertise: Cultures and Technologies of Knowledge00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Resistant to Treatment -- tChapter 2. The Molecular Politics of HIV -- tChapter 3. The Turn toward Africa -- tChapter 4. Research and Development -- tChapter 5. Doing Global Health -- tConclusion -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCountries in sub-Saharan Africa were once dismissed by Western experts as being too poor and chaotic to benefit from the antiretroviral drugs that transformed the AIDS epidemic in the United States and Europe. Today, however, the region is courted by some of the most prestigious research universities in the world as they search for "resource-poor" hospitals in which to base their international HIV research and global health programs. In Scrambling for Africa, Johanna Tayloe Crane reveals how, in the space of merely a decade, Africa went from being a continent largely excluded from advancements in HIV medicine to an area of central concern and knowledge production within the increasingly popular field of global health science.Drawing on research conducted in the U.S. and Uganda during the mid-2000s, Crane provides a fascinating ethnographic account of the transnational flow of knowledge, politics, and research money—as well as blood samples, viruses, and drugs. She takes readers to underfunded Ugandan HIV clinics as well as to laboratories and conference rooms in wealthy American cities like San Francisco and Seattle where American and Ugandan experts struggle to forge shared knowledge about the AIDS epidemic. The resulting uncomfortable mix of preventable suffering, humanitarian sentiment, and scientific ambition shows how global health research partnerships may paradoxically benefit from the very inequalities they aspire to redress. A work of outstanding interdisciplinary scholarship, Scrambling for Africa will be of interest to audiences in anthropology, science and technology studies, African studies, and the medical humanities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAIDS (Disease)xResearchzUganda. 0aMedical anthropologyzUganda. 0aMedical assistance, AmericanzUganda. 4aAfrican Hist & Diaspora. 4aAnthropology. 4aU.S. History. 7aMEDICAL / AIDS & HIV.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146906040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801469060423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801469060/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK